Either way, my point is that I really seriously doubt there will be a 100,000 (1/3) person exodus from EQ in 6 months.  BUT, it has nothing to do with this thread and it's all speculation anyway, so I'll stop talking. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utelivaksk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TelivakSK</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#E9D756>(4/30/01 9:00:34 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All your servers are belong to us Überscore - 4/22</span><hr size=1> Welp, you're right, I forgot AC but the point I made is there.  The gamer population is well over a million actually since EQ boast a claim of 300,000 subscribers alone.  Considering Starcraft and Quake 3 still have about 200,000+ players world wide total, I think it's not unreasonable to assume that when combined with all the other online games out there, the total will easily reach 1 million, if not 2 millions.  As for the 6 months stuff, well, that's definately dependent on the studios which make the games.  Shrugs, maybe by the end of the year would be a better time frame for this dicussion.<br>
<br>
Nextly, the reason why I said the most explosive growth period for MMORPG is over is because, games like EQ/AC/UO tapped a previously left-out pool of population when it comes to online-gaming.  If you noticed, 90% of the online gamers prior to EQ/AO/UO were male, between the age of 12-30.  Basically, young professionals and students who are well-accustomed to technology and the online gaming genre.  Furthermore, a good portion of this population are the same people who played MUDDs, which gave them a introduction of sorts to MMORPG games.  <br>
<br>
EQ/UO/AC tapped the female, family pool of gamers like no other online game have before.  You can't really take the entire population of the computer world into account because like it or not, many people who have never played any computer games before prolly never will.  Not to sound sexist or anything but many women I know will never ever play play hardcore computer games(not counting Solitaire, minesweeper and stuff).  Computer games only appeal to a small portion of the population and that's a fact.  Most gamers now-a-days jump from one game to another.  It is uncommon we see completely new gamers who have never played any computer games before.  Well, that is up until EQ/AC/UO but as I've said, this is pretty much the last pool of the population computer gaming can tap if you rule out the senior citizens and pre-teen children population.<br>
<br>
The other factor in determining computer gaming population is society.  We're still light years away from everyone being completely receptive to computer games and the entertainment value they bring.  I mean, as long as we have so called &quot;expert&quot; condemning &quot;computer game addictation&quot; and people perceiving computer games as &quot;geeky&quot;, we'll never have a total acceptance of computer games amongst the population.  People are slowly coming around but there are still many people who'll never play any computer games.  It's not like you can force them to play, it's a preference thing.  Some people take enjoyment in computer gaming, some people don't.  Right now, most of the population in the countries of the world which computers are common, don't take enjoyment in computer gaming and that's prolly the way it's gonna be.  There's nothing you can say or do that'll change their mind so there's one obstacle for anymore.. explosive growth.<br>
<br>
Lasly, we've already experienced explosive growth during the MUDD era, the Doom2/Quake era and Warcraft2/Starcraft/Total Annihilation/Command&amp;Conquer/Age of Empire era, how much longer can you really expect to continue?  Almost every single genre of computer gaming has been covered.  First person shooter, third person action, real time strat, turn base strat, online RPG, one person RPG, sports sims, flight sims, and combat sims.  You name the genre, it's been established by at least several games.  Oh sure more games will come out that are variations of the existing genres but you're gonna see anything completely revolutionary anymore.  We'd sooner run out of people than games when it comes to online gaming.<br>
<br>
The fact of the matter remains that, as if now, and prolly for the next several years, computer games will only appeal to a minority of the population.  The gaming industry is so trendy, what's hot for one year, may not be so a year later.  That's precisely why I don't see a explosive growth coming anytime soon.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/utelivaksk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TelivakSK</A> at: 4/30/01 9:27:21 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukyphe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>kyphe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#E9D756>(4/30/01 9:51:10 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All your servers are belong to us Überscore - 4/22</span><hr size=1> /em flexes.<br>
